### Generics in Java

Generics enable types (classes and methods) to operate on objects of various types while providing compile-time type safety.

---

### Generic Classes

```java
public class Box<T> {
    private T content;

    public void set(T content) {
        this.content = content;
    }

    public T get() {
        return content;
    }
}

Box<String> stringBox = new Box<>();  // T = String
Box<Integer> intBox = new Box<>();    // T = Integer
```

---

### Generic Methods

```java
public static <T> T getMiddle(T... args) {
    return args[args.length / 2];
}

String mid = getMiddle("a", "b", "c");  // returns "b"
```

---

### Bounded Type Parameters

| Bound | Syntax | Description |
|-------|--------|-------------|
| Upper bound | `<T extends Number>` | T must be Number or subclass |
| Lower bound | `<T super Integer>` | T must be Integer or superclass |
| Multiple bounds | `<T extends A & B & C>` | T must extend all |

---

### Wildcards

| Wildcard | Syntax | Usage |
|----------|--------|-------|
| Unbounded | `List<?>` | Any type |
| Upper bounded | `List<? extends Number>` | Number or subtypes |
| Lower bounded | `List<? super Integer>` | Integer or supertypes |

---

### Type Erasure

Generics are implemented via type erasure. Generic type information is removed at runtime.

```java
List<String> strings = new ArrayList<>();
List<Integer> integers = new ArrayList<>();
// Both are List at runtime
```

> **Key Point:** Generics provide compile-time safety, eliminating the need for explicit casting and preventing ClassCastException. Type parameters use single uppercase letters: T (Type), E (Element), K (Key), V (Value).

codeExample:
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

class Pair<K, V> {
    private K key;
    private V value;

    public Pair(K key, V value) {
        this.key = key;
        this.value = value;
    }

    public K getKey() { return key; }
    public V getValue() { return value; }
}

public class Main {
    public static <T extends Comparable<T>> T max(T a, T b) {
        return a.compareTo(b) > 0 ? a : b;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Pair<String, Integer> pair = new Pair<>("Age", 25);
        System.out.println(pair.getKey() + ": " + pair.getValue());

        System.out.println("Max of 10 and 20: " + max(10, 20));
        System.out.println("Max of A and B: " + max("A", "B"));

        List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
        numbers.add(1);
        numbers.add(2);
        printList(numbers);
    }

    public static void printList(List<?> list) {
        for (Object obj : list) {
            System.out.println(obj);
        }
    }
}
